Adaptive Duty Cycling for Energy Harvesting Systems 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:Harvesting energy from the environment is feasible in many applications to ameliorate the energy limitations in sensor networks .
1-2:In this paper, we present an adaptive duty cycling algorithm that allows energy harvesting sensor nodes to autonomously adjust their duty cycle according to the energy availability in the environment .
1-3:The algorithm has three objectives, namely (a) achieving energy neutral operation, i.e., energy consumption should not be more than the energy provided by the environment, (b) maximizing the system performance based on an application utility model subject to the above energyneutrality constraint, and (c) adapting to the dynamics of the energy source at run time .
1-4:We present a model that enables harvesting sensor nodes to predict future energy opportunities based on historical data .
1-5:We also derive an upper bound on the maximum achievable performance assuming perfect knowledge about the future behavior of the energy source .
1-6:Our methods are evaluated using data gathered from a prototype solar energy harvesting platform and we show that our algorithm can utilize up to 58% more environmental energy compared to the case when harvesting aware power management is not used .
1-7:C.2.4 [Computer Systems Organization]: Computer .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Energy supply has always been a crucial issue in designing battery powered wireless sensor networks because the lifetime and utility of the systems are limited by how long the batteries are able to sustain the operation .
2-2:The fidelity of the data produced by a sensor network begins to degrade once sensor nodes start to run out of battery power .
2-3:Therefore, harvesting energy from the environment has been proposed to supplement or completely replace battery supplies to enhance system lifetime and reduce the maintenance cost of replacing batteries periodically .
2-4:However, metrics for evaluating energy harvesting systems are different from those used for battery powered systems .
2-5:Environmental energy is distinct from battery energy in two ways .
2-6:First it is an inexhaustible supply which, if appropriately used, can allow the system to last forever, unlike the battery which is a limited resource .
2-7:Second, there is an uncertainty associated with its availability and measurement, compared to the energy stored in the battery which can be known deterministically .
2-8:Thus, power management methods based on battery status are not always applicable to energy harvesting systems .
2-9:In addition, most power management schemes designed for battery powered systems only account for the dynamics of the energy consumers (e.g., CPU, radio) but not the dynamics of the energy supply .
2-10:Consequently, battery powered systems usually operate at the lowest performance level that meets the minimum data fidelity requirement in order to maximize the system life .
2-11:Energy harvesting systems, on the other hand, can provide enhanced performance depending on the available energy .
2-12:In this paper, we will study how to adapt the performance of the available energy profile .
2-13:There exist many techniques to accomplish performance scaling at the node level, such as radio transmit power adjustment [1], dynamic voltage scaling [2], and the use of low power modes [3] .
2-14:However, these techniques require hardware support and may not always be available on resource constrained sensor nodes .
2-15:Alternatively, a common performance scaling technique is duty cycling .
2-16:Low power devices typically provide at least one low power mode in which the node is shut down and the power consumption is negligible .
2-17:In addition, the rate of duty cycling is directly related to system performance metrics such as network latency and sampling frequency .
2-18:We will use duty cycle adjustment as the primitive performance scaling technique in our algorithms. .
3 RELATED WORK :
3-1:Energy harvesting has been explored for several different types of systems, such as wearable computers [4], [5], [6], sensor networks [7], etc .
3-2:Several technologies to extract energy from the environment have been demonstrated including solar, motion based, biochemical, vibration based [8], [9], [10], [11], and others are being developed [12], [13] .
3-3:While several energy harvesting sensor node platforms have been prototyped [14], [15], [16], there is a need for systematic power management techniques that provide performance guarantees during system operation .
3-4:The first work to take environmental energy into account for data routing was [17], followed by [18] .
3-5:While these works did demonstrate that environment aware decisions improve performance compared to battery aware decisions, their objective was not to achieve energy neutral operation .
3-6:Our proposed techniques attempt to maximize system performance while maintaining energy neutral operation. .
4 SYSTEM MODEL :
4-1:The energy usage considerations in a harvesting system vary significantly from those in a battery powered system, as mentioned earlier .
4-2:We propose the model shown in Figure 1 for designing energy management methods in a harvesting system .
4-3:The functions of the various blocks shown in the figure are discussed below .
4-4:The precise methods used in our system to achieve these functions will be discussed in subsequent sections .
4-5:Harvested Energy Tracking: This block represents the mechanisms used to measure the energy received from the harvesting device, such as the solar panel .
4-6:Such information is useful for determining the energy availability profile and adapting system performance based on it .
4-7:Collecting this information requires that the node hardware be equipped with the facility to measure the power generated from the environment, and the Heliomote platform [14] we used for evaluating the algorithms has this capability .
4-8:Energy Generation Model: For wireless sensor nodes with limited storage and processing capabilities to be able to use the harvested energy data, models that represent the essential components of this information without using extensive storage are required .
4-9:The purpose of this block is to provide a model for the energy available to the system in a form that may be used for making power management decisions .
4-10:The data measured by the energy tracking block is used here to predict future energy availability .
4-11:A good prediction model should have a low prediction error and provide predicted energy values for durations long enough to make meaningful performance scaling decisions .
4-12:Further, for energy sources that exhibit both long term and short term patterns (e.g., diurnal and climate variations vs .
4-13:weather patterns for solar energy), the model must be able to capture both characteristics .
4-14:Such a model can also use information from external sources such as local weather forecast service to improve its accuracy .
4-15:Energy Consumption Model: It is also important to have detailed information about the energy usage characteristics of the system, at various performance levels .
4-16:For general applicability of our design, we will assume that only one sleep mode is available .
4-17:We assume that the power consumption in the sleep and active modes is known .
4-18:It may be noted that for low power systems with more advanced capabilities such as dynamic voltage scaling (DVS), multiple low power modes, and the capability to shut down system components selectively, the power consumption in each of the states and the resultant effect on application performance should be known to make power management decisions .
4-19:Energy Storage Model: This block represents the model for the energy storage technology .
4-20:Since all the generated energy may not be used instantaneously, the harvesting system will usually have some energy storage technology .
4-21:Storage technologies (e.g., batteries and ultra capacitors) are non ideal, in that there is some energy loss while storing and retrieving energy from them .
4-22:These characteristics must be known to efficiently manage energy usage and storage .
4-23:This block also includes the system capability to measure the residual stored energy .
4-24:Most low power systems use batteries to store energy and provide residual battery status .
4-25:This is commonly based on measuring the battery voltage which is then mapped to the residual battery energy using the known charge to voltage relationship for the battery technology in use .
4-26:More sophisticated methods which track the flow of energy into and out of the battery are also available .
4-27:Harvesting aware Power Management: The inputs provided by the previously mentioned blocks are used here to determine the suitable power management strategy for the system .
4-28:Power management could be carried to meet different objectives in different applications .
4-29:For instance, in some systems, the harvested energy may marginally supplement the battery supply and the objective may be to maximize the system lifetime .
4-30:A more interesting case is when the harvested energy is used as the primary source of energy for the system with the objective of achieving indefinitely long system lifetime .
4-31:In such cases, the power management objective is to achieve energy neutral operation .
4-32:In other words, the system should only use as much energy as harvested from the environment and attempt to maximize performance within this available energy budget. .
